Function to prepare data frame for products

prepare_products <- function(df){
  # Removing the redundancy of the id from the end of the NombreProducto
  df <- df %>% mutate(NombreProducto = gsub('\\d+$', '', NombreProducto))
  
  # Putting the product name into a new variable
  df <- df %>% mutate(Product = gsub('  ', ' ', gsub(' +$', '', str_extract(NombreProducto, '[^\\d]+'))))
  
  # Putting the brand into a new variable and removing its spaces
  df <- df %>%
    mutate(Brand = str_extract(NombreProducto, '\\w+ $'))
  df <- df %>% mutate(Brand = gsub(' ', '', Brand))
  
  # Putting the weight in grams into a new variable
  df <- df %>%
    mutate(
      Weight_grams = str_extract(NombreProducto, '\\d+(?=\\s*g)|\\d+(?=\\s*G)'),
      Weight_kg = str_extract(NombreProducto, '\\d+(?=\\s*Kg)|\\d+(?=\\s*kg)'),
      Weight_grams = if_else(!is.na(Weight_grams), Weight_grams, as.character(as.numeric(Weight_kg) * 1000))
    ) %>%
    select(-Weight_kg)
  
  # Putting the quantities into a new variable
  df <- df %>%
    mutate(
      Quantity = str_extract(NombreProducto, '\\d+(?=\\s*p)'))
  
  # Putting the volumes into a new variable
  df <- df %>%
    mutate(
      Volume = str_extract(NombreProducto, '\\d+(?=\\s*ml)|\\d+(?=\\s* ml)'))
  
  # Removing the stopwords
  df_2 <- df
  df_2 <- df_2 %>% mutate(Product = removeWords(Product, stopwords_es))
  
  # Subsetting the dataset
  df_3 <- df_2[, c(1,3)]
  # Combining into product names
  df<- df_2[-2] %>%
    mutate(
      Product = paste(Product, ' ', Brand, sep = ''),
      Product = if_else(!is.na(Weight_grams), paste(Product,' ', Weight_grams, 'g', sep = ''), Product),
      Product = if_else(!is.na(Quantity), paste(Product,' ', Quantity, 'p', sep = ''), Product),
      Product = if_else(!is.na(Volume), paste(Product,' ', Volume, 'ml', sep = ''), Product)) %>%
    select(Producto_ID, Product)
  
  return(df)
}

As checked on the plot, the channels 1 and 5 have more than 80% of the returns. Since constraints by channel have not been informed, at this point it will be suggested to integrate the total of demand to all channels by sharing the total of sells. So, channel will not be considered in the following analyses. The route will also not be considered, since it’s to do to the strategy of transportation.

The IDs (Agencia, Cliente and Producto) could be categoric variables. But, to guarantee that possible future data won’t be duplicated by using different IDs, it will be considered to use the description for each one: Town for Agencia_ID, NombreCliente for Cliente_ID, Product for Producto_ID.

Products Analysis

products_analysis <- train_set[,c(6, 10:14)]
products_analysis <- distinct(products_analysis %>%
                                group_by(Product) %>%
                                mutate(
                                  Venta_uni_hoy = sum(Venta_uni_hoy),
                                  Venta_hoy = sum(Venta_hoy),
                                  Dev_uni_proxima = sum(Dev_uni_proxima),

                                  Demanda_uni_equil = sum(Demanda_uni_equil)
                                ), Product, .keep_all = T)

Checking the number of products

length(unique(products_analysis$Product))
## [1] 815

Since the number of products reaches to 815, it’s considered too much to address throught. So, the Pareto’s Theorem will be considered to sub set the products that represent 80% of the total of Demand, Return in units or Return in pesos. To choose the best strategy will be chosen the dataset with the lowest number of products and the highest potential to reduce the number of returns.

As seen above, a small parcel of the products represent 80% of de DEMAND, RETURNED UNITS AND COSTS WITH RETURNS. At this point it’s being considered to address through the products which represent about 80% of the returned units in a trying to reduce wastes. By focusing on the features with the most returns, it can be reached multiple benefits, for example: costs reduction, better use of transports, improvement on the relationship with clients.

Functions to calculate the demand

Before define the method that will be used to predict the demand, it was suggested to test if the data set is able to be handle by a linear regression. To be able, it’s important that there are multiple occurrences of combined variables (Product, Town, NombreCliente) to train the model and then make the predictions. To guarantee a fast and efficient return, it will be considered the lists of products, town and client, compiled throughout previous analysis: list_products: list of products which represent 80% of the total of returned units list_towns: list of towns which represent 80% of the total of returned units from the list_products list_clients: list of towns which represent 80% of the total of returned units from the list_towns

train_set_result <- train_set %>% filter(Product %in% list_products & Town %in% list_towns & NombreCliente %in% list_clients)

Since the Dev_uni_proxima has to do to the returned units per week, it’s important to focus on the Town and Client. So it’s recommended to reduce the mean of returns calculated by week as in the function

This function returns the combination of Product, Town and Client per week, ordered by the most returned products from set which most impacts in about 51% of the returns.

By this function, it’s possible to adjust the combined variables with efficiency

suggested_demand <- function(){
  result <- distinct(train_set_result %>%
                         group_by(Product, Town, NombreCliente, Semana) %>%
                         mutate(
                           Return_mean = mean(Dev_uni_proxima),
                           Demand_min = min(Demanda_uni_equil),
                           Demand_max = max(Demanda_uni_equil),
                           Demand_mean = mean(Demanda_uni_equil)
                         ), Town, NombreCliente, Semana, .keep_all = T)
  result <- result[, c(1:4, 10:13)]
  kable(head(result[order(-result$Return_mean), ], 50), caption = '50 first results')
  }

This function lists the combination of Town and Client per week, ordered by the highest number of returns of the Product which was choosed by the user.

return_demand_product <- function(prod){
  result <- train_set %>% filter(Product == prod)
  result_2 <- distinct(result %>%
                         group_by(Town, NombreCliente, Semana) %>%
                         mutate(
                           Return_mean = mean(Dev_uni_proxima),
                           Demand_min = min(Demanda_uni_equil),
                           Demand_max = max(Demanda_uni_equil),
                           Demand_mean = mean(Demanda_uni_equil)
                         ), Town, NombreCliente, Semana, .keep_all = T)
  result_2 <- result_2[, c(2, 4, 6, 7, 15:18)]
  kable(head(result_2[order(-result_2$Return_mean), ], 50), caption = '50 first results')
}

Final notes

It’s been presented variables which can be used to ponder the demand:
Demand_min: minimum of demand per week
Demand_max: maximum of demand per week
Demand_mean: mean of demand per week

With these numbers, it can be limit the maximum number of products of a specific variable combination, and ponder if the orders are reasonable. With new datas, this script can be run again and as the returns descrease, new combined features will be shown.
